[1]
Date: Sat, 4 Aug 2007
Source: FMD News circular [edited]
Follow-up: outbreak reported in Surrey
-----------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY: Latest news on the FMD outbreak reported in Surrey:
* Early today the European Commission released a
statement about the outbreak stating: "The
Commission will adopt on Monday an emergency
decision confirming the measures being applied in
accordance with EC legislation, concerning
restrictions on the movement of animals and the
dispatch of products from the UK."
* Speaking on Radio 4`s Today programme Peter
Kendall, the president of the National Farmers
Union, said the farming industry would not oppose
the use of vaccination of livestock if that was
the scientific advice. He said: "Certainly as an
industry we would not stand in any way to object
to vaccination if the scientists deem it the right way of moving forward."
* Cobra, the Government`s emergency committee,
was set to meet today [Sat, 4 Aug 2007] at 9am.
* Although the farm`s exact location has not been
disclosed, a map on Defra`s website shows the
centre of the protection zone between Farnborough
and Aldershot. [See page 3 of the pdf document
available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/fmd/pdf/declaration-pz-sz-rz-070803.pdf>.
- Mod. AS].
* Three major agricultural shows in Scotland are
going ahead this weekend without cows, sheep and
goats, due to foot-and-mouth restrictions.
* Scientists are carrying out tests to determine
whether the virus reached Britain through the
illegal movement of animals, on the wind or by
accidental contamination. ``The laboratory tests
are already under way and the earliest possible
information will probably come during the later
part of today,`` said the country`s chief veterinarian, Debby Reynolds.
FULL TEXT:
<http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/08/04/ndefra704.xml>.
--
