Communicated by:
Patricia Doyle, PhD
<dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
[One of the main conditions for successful
containment and eradication of the outbreak is
timely and complete backward and forward tracing
of contact animals. The virus has been
circulating within the affected premises during a
certain period before being suspected and
subsequently confirmed; the duration of that
period (which is, in practical terms, never
shorter than 10 days but could be much longer),
should be determined and all possible contacts
traced. Determining the age of the FMD
lesions is a useful aid to determining the
approximate time of first infection and of the
period during which the virus could have spread
to other sites before the visible onset of disease.
We wish DEFRA success in this crucial
undertaking, and look forward to the pathogen's typing. - Mod.AS]
